{"id": "chunk_00068", "text": "# FILE: Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf # CATEGORY: Training & Competency # SIZE: 1011362 bytes ### Page 1 Training Needs Assessment Report HR Center of Excellence Learning & Culture Apr. 2025 ### Page 2 Generate Version 1 of Training Needs PlanGenerate theversion1 of the training needs resultsStakeholder Engagement During RamadanAnalyse Performance Appraisal Results TNA Version 2 produced and sent to HRBPs to delete first version and use new one.Final Training Plan One-to-One with heads of Depts. in branches, and offices At least 3 - 4 senior leaders in each TNA Process ### Page 3 Introduction This report provides a comprehensive overview of the key training and developmental needs across SGH branches, identified through various sources of information.", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00069", "text": "ning and developmental needs across SGH branches, identified through various sources of information. The findings aim to guide targeted learning interventions to enhance staff capabilities , leadership effectiveness, and service excellence in alignment with SGH’s strategic priorities for the year 2025. ### Page 4 Table of Contents ### Page 5 TNA Objectives ### Page 6 TNA Objectives 1.Identify recurring skill gaps and behavioral challenges across clinical and non -clinical divisions. 2.Ensure training priorities align with SGH’s strategic pillars, “Caring like Family” culture, and our competency framework. 3.Support performance improvement for anyone rated “meeting” or “below expectations” in recent appraisal cycles.", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00070", "text": "rformance improvement for anyone rated “meeting” or “below expectations” in recent appraisal cycles. 4.Capture stakeholder observations on how core and leadership competencies are applied in daily practice. 5.Respond to external healthcare trends and competitive pressures by enhancing staff readiness and agility. 6.Provide a data -informed foundation for the 2025 learning and development plan. ### Page 7 Data Collection Methodology 8 Data Sources ### Page 8 Data Collection Methodology This TNA was informed by a combination of quantitative data and qualitative insights from the following sources: 1.Performance appraisal results from the 2024 cycle, focusing on individuals rated as “meeting” or “below” expectations.", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00071", "text": "sal results from the 2024 cycle, focusing on individuals rated as “meeting” or “below” expectations. 2.Areas of development mentioned by the direct manager of the assessed individual, highlighting key growth areas identified during performance evaluations. ### Page 9 Data Collection Methodology 3.Structured interviews - total of 23 interviews were conducted across branches, including MEAHCO Cairo and Jeddah.", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00072", "text": "terviews - total of 23 interviews were conducted across branches, including MEAHCO Cairo and Jeddah. Interviews conducted as follows: Data for this analysis was collected through structured interviews with key stakeholders in each branch (see appendix 1), including: •Chief Medical Officer (CMO) •Chief Nursing Officer (CNO) or Nurse Educator •Patient Experience (PX) Manager •Human Resources Business Partner (HRBP) •Some Heads of Divisions in MEAHCO Egypt/ Jeddah Each stakeholder provided insights into: •Their respective division’s training needs , •The needs of other divisions they serve as internal customers, •Recurrent behavioral challenges related to core and leadership competencies .", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00073", "text": "s internal customers, •Recurrent behavioral challenges related to core and leadership competencies . •Best training method and duration/ day for their staff Stakeholders were asked to share examples of observed competency gaps , especially those that recur across settings and influence patient experience or operational efficiency. ### Page 10 Data Collection Methodology 4.SGH Core/ Leadership Competency Framework , outlining expected behaviors standards. 5.SGH Strategic Pillars , ensuring alignment between learning investments and long - term organizational goals. 6.Patient complaints , providing visibility into service quality gaps from the patient’s perspective. 7.Internal customer perspectives , reflecting interdepartmental challenges and support gaps.", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00074", "text": "ective. 7.Internal customer perspectives , reflecting interdepartmental challenges and support gaps. 8.Global healthcare trends and benchmarks , helping contextualize SGH's needs within broader industry expectations and innovations. ### Page 11 Emerging Healthcare Trends Impacting Staff Competency Requirements in KSA In alignment with CBAHI HR.10.2.4, the TNA process also considered key developments and trends within the healthcare industry in Saudi Arabia . The following themes were identified as particularly relevant for SGH staff development in 2025:1. Shift Toward Patient -Centered and Value -Based Care The transition from volume - to value -based healthcare under Vision 2030 emphasizes outcome -driven service delivery.", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00075", "text": "m volume - to value -based healthcare under Vision 2030 emphasizes outcome -driven service delivery. Staff must strengthen their skills in empathetic communication , shared decision -making, and patient advocacy . 2. Digital Transformation and Technological Agility Widespread adoption of electronic medical records (EMRs), telehealth, AI, and data -driven decision tools necessitates enhanced digital literacy and workflow adaptability across all functions. 3. Market Competition and Privatization Pressure The growth of private hospitals and mega healthcare projects has intensified competition. SGH staff are expected to demonstrate consistent professionalism, accountability , and superior service delivery to retain patient trust . 4.", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00076", "text": "sistent professionalism, accountability , and superior service delivery to retain patient trust . 4. Cultural Intelligence and Service Expectations An increasingly diverse patient base, combined with rising service expectations, calls for better cultural sensitivity, active listening , and positive engagement — especially among frontliners. 5. Accreditation and Regulatory Readiness With CBAHI, JCI, and MoL compliance becoming more central to healthcare operations, all staff must maintain high standards in documentation , infection control, safety, and policy adherence. 6. Workforce Nationalization (Saudization) As more Saudi nationals join healthcare roles, focus on developing key skills such as cultural competency, effective communication, patient -centered care, and time management.", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
{"id": "chunk_00077", "text": "s such as cultural competency, effective communication, patient -centered care, and time management. Additionally, offering training in digital literacy, basic leadership , and stress management will help ensure their successful integration, growth, and retention within the organization. ### Page 12 TNA Detailed Results ➢Organization Level ➢Division Level ➢Branch - Specific Needs ### Page 13 1. Organization -Level Training Needs Division/ Job RoleTraining Need/Skill GapRecommended Training CoursesCore / Leadership CompetenciesStrategic Pillars All Staff Lack of Ownership& Accountability Poor Patient Care Mindset Lack of Emotional Intelligence (including the /5 components), Poor Communication SkillsBuilding Personal Accountability Patient -Care Mindset Emotional Intelligence for Healthcare", "metadata": {"source": "Riyadh TNA Report (2).pdf", "category": "Training & Competency", "owner": "Mohamed Fekri Soliman", "pii_status": "anonymized"}}
